%opening
\title{Puzzle}
\author{}
\date{}

\begin{document}

\thispagestyle{empty}
First, numbers $24$ through $55$ are Egyptian.  Behold:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item[24.] 2+4+6+12
	\item[25.] 5+5+5+5+5
	\item[26.] 4+4+6+6+6
	\item[27.] 3+6+6+6+6
	\item[28.] 4+4+4+8+8
	\item[29.] 2+3+12+12
	\item[30.] 2+3+10+15
	\item[31.] 2+4+5+20
	\item[32.] 2+3+9+18
	\item[33.] 3+3+9+9+9
	\item[34.] 2+8+8+8+8
	\item[35.] 2+6+9+9+9
	\item[36.] 2+6+8+8+12
	\item[37.] 2+3+8+24
	\item[38.] 2+6+6+12+12
	\item[39.] 2+6+6+10+15
	\item[40.] 4+4+8+8+8+8
	\item[41.] 2+6+6+9+18
	\item[42.] 2+4+12+12+12
	\item[43.] 2+4+10+12+15
	\item[44.] 3+3+6+8+24
	\item[45.] 2+4+9+12+18
	\item[46.] 2+4+8+16+16
	\item[47.] 3+4+8+8+12+12
	\item[48.] 3+4+8+8+10+15
	\item[49.] 3+4+6+12+12+12
	\item[50.] 2+4+8+12+24
	\item[51.] 3+3+5+10+30
	\item[52.] 2+5+5+20+20
	\item[53.] 2+5+6+10+30
	\item[54.] 2+3+7+42
	\item[55.] 2+4+7+14+28
\end{enumerate}

We now show by induction that all numbers greater than 55 are
Egyptian.  Suppose that all numbers from 24 through $2(x-1) + 8,
2(x-1) + 9$ are Egyptian, where $x$ is an integer such that $2(x-1) + 9 \geq 55$.  Then $2x
+ 8 \geq 56$ implies that $x \geq 24$ and is Egyptian.  Let $x = a_1 +
\cdots + a_k$ be such that $1/a_1 + \cdots + 1/a_k = 1$.  Then
\[
	2x + 8 = 2(a_1 + \cdots + a_k) + 8 = 2a_1 + \cdots + 2a_k + 4 + 4
\]
and
\[
1/(2a_1) + \cdots + 1/(2a_k) + 1/4 + 1/4
	= (1/2)(1/a_1 + \cdots + 1/a_k) + 1/2 = 1.
\]
and also
\[
	2x + 9 = 2(a_1 + \cdots + a_k) + 9 = 2a_1 + \cdots + 2a_k + 3 + 6
\]
and
\[
	1/(2a_1) + \cdots + 1/(2a_k) + 1/3 + 1/6
	= (1/2)(1/a_1 + \cdots + 1/a_k) + 1/2 = 1.
\]


\end{document}

